The thing with "Dzie≈Ñ ≈õwira" is that it's very... Polish. You would of course appreciate the general tragicomism of it, but the scathing look at Poland and its people would probably largely be lost on you. The protagonist (anti-hero?) is frustrated not only by his personal failures, but also by the country he lives in. The sad fate of the intelgencja* (intelligentsia, to you) after the 1989 transformation is at the core of the film. It's all painfully poignant to an intelligent and disillusioned Polish viewer. An intelligent and disillusioned American might feel lost in places. So don't go out of your way looking for it. It would be best if we could watch it together. I'd rather you didn't hold my hand though. Or other bits. 

